07820nam a22011415i 9783110618549DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831106185497 a10.1515/97831106185492doi  a(DE-B1597)499918  a(OCoLC)1138546288  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aBS1245.55b.E96 2020 7aREL0066302bisacsh04a222/.12007122300aExodus :bBorder Crossings in Jewish, Christian and Islamic Texts and Images /ced. by Annette Hoffmann. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (VI, 253 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJudaism, Christianity, and Islam – Tension, Transmission, Transformation ,x2196-405X ;v1100tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction -- tThe Way Out of Vassalage – The Exodus Narrative (Ex 1–14) and Ancient International Law -- tThe Exodus Narrative and Divine Warfare in the Dura-Europos Synagogue -- tThrough Water and Stone: The Brescia Sarcophagus Crossing of the Red Sea -- t“Prolific Writing”: Retracing a Desert Palimpsest in the South Sinai -- tBewegung in der Altdeutschen Exodus als Heilsempfang und Übersetzung -- tPurim Like Yom Kippurim: Between the Texts and Images of the London Miscellany and R. Eleazar the Preacher’s Commentary on Exodus -- tThe Crossing of Boundaries and Liminality in the Rabbinic Aggadot on the Death of Moses and on “Those to Die in the Wilderness”: Analogous Aspects -- tBetween Heaven and Earth: The Illustration of the Death of Moses in Rashid al-Din’s Jami al-Tawarikh (World History) -- tThe Prophet Muhammad’s Visionary Journey to Jerusalem – a Spiritual Exodus -- tThe Paradigm of a Second Exodus in Jewish Tradition -- t„Du hast die Greuel gesehen…“. Zum Exodus als ästhetischer Unterscheidungskraft -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tPhoto Credits0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe scientific debates on border crossings and cultural exchange between Judaism, Christianity, and Islam have much increased over the last decades. Within this context, however, little attention has been given to the biblical Exodus, which not only plays a pivotal role in the Abrahamic religions, but also is a master narrative of a border crossing in itself. Sea and desert are spaces of liminality and transit in more than just a geographical sense. Their passage includes a transition to freedom and initiation into a new divine community, an encounter with God and an entry into the Age of law. The volume gathers twelve articles written by leading specialists in Jewish and Islamic Studies, Theology and Literature, Art and Film history, dedicated to the transitional aspects within the Exodus narrative. Bringing these studies together, the volume takes a double approach, one that is both comparative and intercultural. How do Jewish, Christian and Islamic texts and images read and retell the various border crossings in the Exodus story, and on what levels do they interrelate? By raising these questions the volume aims to contribute to a deeper understanding of contact points between the various traditions.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aAbrahamic religions. 0aBorder crossingxReligious aspects. 4aChristentum. 4aExodus. 4aIslam. 4aJudentum. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Studies / History & Culture.2bisacsh  aChristianity.  aExodus.  aIslam.  aJudaism.1 aHoffmann, Annette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoffmann, Annette, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHoll, Ute, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKushelevsky, Rella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLarison